 ideally would be about equal in magnitude to the minimum residual. In this case, it is much larger than the minimum, which helps us see that the residuals are likely right skewed. Coefficients: Notice that in your glm(‚Ä¶) you used only \(Y\) and \(X\). You did type out any coefficients, i.e., the \( eta_0\) or \( eta_1\) of the regression model. These coefficients are estimated by the glm(‚Ä¶) function and displayed in this part of the output along with standard errors, t-values, and p-values. ¬† Estimate To learn more about the ‚ÄúEstimates‚Äù of the ‚ÄúCoefficients‚Äù see the ‚ÄúExplanation‚Äù tab, ‚ÄúEstimating the Model Parameters‚Äù section for details. Error To learn more about the ‚ÄúStandard Errors‚Äù of the ‚ÄúCoefficients‚Äù see the ‚ÄúExplanation‚Äù tab, ‚ÄúInference for the Model Parameters‚Äù section. ¬† z value The Z-score testing the hypothesis that \( eta_j=0\) ¬† Pr(>|z|) The p-value for the corresponding Z-score. (Intercept) This always says ‚ÄúIntercept‚Äù for any glm(‚Ä¶) you run in R. That is because R always assumes there is a y-intercept for your regression function. ¬† -4.97603 This is the estimate of the y-intercept, \( eta_0\). It is called \(b_0\). It is the average y-value when X is zero. ¬† 0.65316 This is the standard error of \(b_0\). It tells you how much \(b_0\) varies from sample to sample. The closer to zero, the better. -7.618 Z-score for \(b_0\). 2.57e-14 This is the p-value of the test of the hypothesis that \( eta_0 = 0\). It measures the probability of observing a Z-value as extreme as the one observed. To compute it yourself in R, use pnorm(-abs(your z-value))*2. *** This is called a ‚Äústar‚Äù. Three stars means significant at the 0.01 level of \(\alpha\). Time This is always the name of your X-variable in your glm(Y ~ X, ‚Ä¶). ¬† 0.39111 This is the estimate of the slope, \( eta_1\). It is called \(b_1\). It is the change in the average y-value as X is increased by 1 unit. ¬† 0.04979 This is the standard error of \(b_1\). It tells you how much \(b_1\) varies from sample to sample. The closer to zero, the better. 7.854 Z-score for \(b_1\). 4.02e-15 This is the p-value of the test of the hypothesis that \( eta_1 = 0\). To compute it yourself in R, use pt(-abs(your t-value), df of your regression)*2 *** This is called a ‚Äústar‚Äù. Three stars means significant at the 0.01 level of \(\alpha\). Diet2 This is always the name of your X-variable in your glm(Y ~ X, ‚Ä¶). ¬† 0.58283 This is the estimate of the change in the intercept, \( eta_2\). It is called \(b_2\). ¬† 1.04061 This is the standard error of \(b_2\). It tells you how much \(b_2\) varies from sample to sample. The closer to zero, the better. 0.560 Z-score for \(b_2\). 0.5754 This is the p-value of the test of the hypothesis that \( eta_2 = 0\). To compute it yourself in R, use pt(-abs(your t-value), df of your regression)*2 Diet3 This is always the name of your X-variable in your glm(Y ~ X, ‚Ä¶). ¬† -8.44476 This is the estimate of the change in the intercept, \( eta_3\). It is called \(b_3\). ¬† 4.32324 This is the standard error of \(b_3\). It tells you how much \(b_3\) varies from sample to sample. The closer to zero, the better. -1.953 Z-score for \(b_3\). 0.0508 This is the p-value of the test of the hypothesis that \( eta_3 = 0\). To compute it yourself in R, use pt(-abs(your t-value), df of your regression)*2 . This is called a period. It means significant at the 0.1 level of \(\alpha\). Diet4 This is always the name of your X-variable in your glm(Y ~ X, ‚Ä¶). ¬† -67.41995 This is the estimate of the change in the intercept, \( eta_4\). It is called \(b_4\). ¬† 3768.10023 This is the standard error of \(b_4\). It tells you how much \(b_4\) varies from sample to sample. The closer to zero, the better. -0.018 Z-score for \(b_4\). 0.9857 This is the p-value of the test of the hypothesis that \( eta_2 = 0\). To compute it yourself in R, use pt(-abs(your t-value), df of your regression)*2 Time:Diet2 This is always the name 