eq}}ight\} \ 	ext{some number, but typically 0}\) Examples: sleepInd student1 student2 R Instructions Console Help Command: ?t.test() There are two ways to perform the test. Option 1: t.test(Y ~ X, data = YourData, mu = YourNull, alternative = YourAlternative, conf.level = 0.95) Y must be a ‚Äúnumeric‚Äù vector from YourData that represents the data for both samples. X must be a ‚Äúfactor‚Äù or ‚Äúcharacter‚Äù vector from YourData that represents the group assignment for each observation. There can only be two groups specified in this column of data. YourNull is the numeric value from your null hypothesis for \(\mu_1-\mu_2\). YourAlternative is one of the three options: "two.sided", "greater", "less" and should correspond to your alternative hypothesis. The value for conf.level = 0.95 can be changed to any desired confidence level, like 0.90 or 0.99. It should correspond to \(1-\alpha\). Testing Assumptions library(car) qqPlot(Y ~ X, data=YourData) Example Code Hover your mouse over the example codes to learn more. t.test( ‚Äòt.test‚Äô is an R function that performs one and two sample t-tests. length¬† ‚Äòlength‚Äô is a quantitative variable (numeric vector). ~¬† ‚Äò~‚Äô is the tilde symbol. sex,¬† ‚Äòsex‚Äô is a ‚Äòfactor‚Äô or ‚Äòcharacter‚Äô vector that represents the group assignment for each observation. There are two groups. data=KidsFeet,¬† ‚ÄòKidsFeet‚Äô is a dataset in library(mosaic). Type View(KidsFeet) to view it. mu = 0,¬† The numeric value from the null hypothesis for Œº1-Œº2 is 0 meaning the null hypothesis is \(\mu1-\mu2 = 0\) alternative = ‚Äútwo.sided‚Äù,¬† The alternative is ‚Äútwo-sided‚Äù meaning the alternative hypothesis is \(\mu1-\mu2 
